(87,59,1,'Counting Moves','[{\"number\":1,\"type\":\"info\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In the endgame, it\'s common to be required to calculate many moves before making the right decision. That\'s where move counting comes in handy.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":2,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In the example below, white has two options:<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":3,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<ol start=\\\"1\\\"><li>Capture the g6 and h5 pawns and go for a queen.<\\/li><\\/ol>\"},{\"number\":4,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<ol start=\\\"2\\\" class=\\\"mb-2\\\"><li>Prevent black from capturing b5 and a6 Pawns and pushing the b-pawn forward.<\\/li><\\/ol>\"},{\"number\":5,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">If white can queen first, the first option would be the right one. The way you calculate this position is by counting.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":6,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">White has eight moves until promotion, and black has nine. From these numbers, we know that when white promotes the pawn, black will be two moves away from queening. Thus, it would be wise to go for the first option.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":7,\"type\":\"chess-lesson\",\"content\":{\"position\":\"8\\/p2k4\\/Pp4p1\\/1P5p\\/5K1P\\/6P1\\/8\\/8 w - - 0 1\",\"chessState\":{\"moveHistory\":[{\"fen\":\"8\\/p2k4\\/Pp4p1\\/1P5p\\/5K1P\\/6P1\\/8\\/8 w - - 0 1\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"af0f9f80-0861-11ed-8436-f1acf42a644d\",\"firstSquare\":38,\"secondSquare\":31,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"},{\"id\":\"af7f9f60-0861-11ed-8436-f1acf42a644d\",\"firstSquare\":23,\"secondSquare\":32,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"},{\"id\":\"afe2a6f0-0861-11ed-8436-f1acf42a644d\",\"firstSquare\":47,\"secondSquare\":39,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"},{\"id\":\"b011a630-0861-11ed-8436-f1acf42a644d\",\"firstSquare\":39,\"secondSquare\":31,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"},{\"id\":\"b0c69e50-0861-11ed-8436-f1acf42a644d\",\"firstSquare\":31,\"secondSqua