(173,111,2,'Bishop and Pawn vs. Knight','[{\"number\":1,\"type\":\"info\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In bishop and pawn against knight endgames, the defending side should keep the knight away from the opposing king. That\'s because the attacker will be less likely to put the opponent in zugzwang.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":2,\"type\":\"warning\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">It\'s important to note that in some positions, the attacker would be unable to put the defender in zugzwang even when the defender\'s knight is close to the attacker\'s king.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":3,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In the example below, black\'s knight is now on b6. White has no way to put black in zugzwang. The game ends in a draw.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":4,\"type\":\"chess-lesson\",\"content\":{\"position\":\"8\\/8\\/1n1PK3\\/2k5\\/8\\/8\\/6B1\\/8 w - - 0 1\",\"chessState\":{\"moveHistory\":[{\"fen\":\"8\\/8\\/1n1PK3\\/2k5\\/8\\/8\\/6B1\\/8 w - - 0 1\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"player\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"8\\/8\\/1n1PK3\\/2k5\\/8\\/5B2\\/8\\/8 b - - 1 1\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[55,46],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"0c362960-4979-11ed-9a87-338d6d6153eb\",\"firstSquare\":55,\"secondSquare\":46,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"}],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"engine\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"8\\/8\\/1n1PK3\\/8\\/2k5\\/5B2\\/8\\/8 w - - 2 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[27,35],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"0d317950-4979-11ed-9a87-338d6d6153eb\",\"firstSquare\":27,\"secondSquare\":35,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"}],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"player\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"8\\/8\\/1n1PK3\\/3B4\\/2k5\\/8\\/8\\/8 b - - 3 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[46,28],\"checkSquare\":35,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"0e2f8860-4979-11ed-9a87-338d6d6153eb\",\"firstSquare\":46,\"secondSquare\":28,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"}],\"h