(177,114,2,'Knight and Pawn vs. Bishop','[{\"number\":1,\"type\":\"info\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In some positions where the pawn has not reached the 7th rank, the bishop can prevent the queening even without the king\'s help. That\'s possible when the bishop\'s diagonal is at least five squares long, allowing the bishop to maneuver (the king and knight together can only control four squares). Otherwise, the bishop will need the king\'s help to stop the pawn.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":2,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">Look at the example below. Let\'s imagine that it\'s white\'s turn to move. White will play Nf6 to block the bishop (interference) and win the game. But since it\'s black\'s turn to move, the position is drawn.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":3,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In the previous example, the bishop could not prevent the queening, but now it\'s different. The bishop has more space to maneuver, and the draw is inevitable.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":4,\"type\":\"chess-lesson\",\"content\":{\"position\":\"8\\/5K2\\/4P3\\/3N2b1\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7k b - - 0 1\",\"chessState\":{\"moveHistory\":[{\"fen\":\"8\\/5K2\\/4P3\\/3N2b1\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7k b - - 0 1\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"player\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"3b4\\/5K2\\/4P3\\/3N4\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7k w - - 1 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[31,4],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"4947e480-4990-11ed-a6b6-39074007f261\",\"firstSquare\":31,\"secondSquare\":4,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"}],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"engine\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"3bK3\\/8\\/4P3\\/3N4\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7k b - - 2 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[14,5],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"4c4a4f10-4990-11ed-a6b6-39074007f261\",\"firstSquare\":14,\"secondSquare\":5,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"},{\"id\":\"4cf423a0-4990-11ed-a6b6-39074007f261\",\"firstSquare\":5,\"secondSquar