(183,118,3,'Draw Techniques','[{\"number\":1,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">In the example below, we see the same position as the previous position but with black to move. Black can secure the draw by checking the opponent\'s king from the side.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":2,\"type\":\"warning\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">The rook side checks secure the draw when the black rook is at least three squares away from the pawn, and the white rook is misplaced and can\'t block the side checks.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":3,\"type\":\"html\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">If we shift all the pieces (except the black rook) one file to the left, the checks will not secure the draw since white can use the king to attack the rook.<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":4,\"type\":\"info\",\"content\":\"<p class=\\\"mb-2\\\">Central or bishop pawn divides the board into short and long sides. The defender should keep the king on the shorter side and the rook on the longer side (In the example below, the left side is the long one (h, g, f, e), and the right side is the short one (c, b, a)).<\\/p>\"},{\"number\":5,\"type\":\"chess-lesson\",\"content\":{\"position\":\"3K4\\/1k1P4\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7r\\/2R5 b - - 0 1\",\"chessState\":{\"moveHistory\":[{\"fen\":\"3K4\\/1k1P4\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/7r\\/2R5 b - - 0 1\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"player\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"3K3r\\/1k1P4\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/2R5 w - - 1 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[56,8],\"checkSquare\":4,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"07caa0c0-4a5c-11ed-8456-71ba1e3aa567\",\"firstSquare\":56,\"secondSquare\":8,\"color\":\"#EFB701\"}],\"highlightedSquares\":[],\"toMove\":\"engine\",\"newMove\":false},{\"fen\":\"7r\\/1k1PK3\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/8\\/2R5 b - - 2 2\",\"sound\":\"move\",\"lastMoves\":[4,13],\"checkSquare\":null,\"arrows\":[{\"id\":\"08fe3ec0-4a5c-11ed-8456-71ba1e3aa567\",\"firstSquare\":4,\"secondSquare\":13,\"color\"